media.altText:
Anxiety, Depression, and Exercise

Over 7% (over 500 million) of the world population deal with anxiety and/or depression. A recent study of over 1000 trials with over 120,000 participants has shown that, doing regular exercise can reduce the symptoms of mild to moderate depression and anxiety. This study found that exercising regularly has more impact on reduction of symptoms than medication and psychotherapy. Exercise helps release hormones that increase the mood, influences neurotransmitters, and it can help get away from the cycle of negative thoughts. Doing around 20 minutes of exercise a day has shown a significant reduction of depression, anxiety, and stress. 

If you are dealing with mental health issues, consider including regular exercise into your routine, whether it's brisk walking, yoga, swimming, lifting weights, or short high-intensity workouts.
